				<li id="16673227" class="cmnt-root" data="7" data-d="1652098824000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t578211/Law-of-Causality" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">09 May 2022 08:20</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16673227" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">The best use I&apos;ve found for this is with a Colossal weapon with a good physical block. I&apos;ve been using it with the Royal Greatsword which justifies the INT investment, but there are possibly better choices. Since the sword doesn&apos;t block all the damage, Causality ticks from blocking, so if you&apos;re dealing with something too quick to easily hit you just block, let Causality go off and flatten them, and follow up with the weapon whilst the target&apos;s down.<br/>Possibly even better would be using the Icon Shield and a Great Stars with Prayerful Strike. Block with the 95% GS, let Causality proc, then Prayerful Strike to get all the HP back.</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16673227" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16673227" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">0</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>7</p><i class="add">+1</i></section><sect